We called each other &quot;Bro&quot; short for brother in Nam, it was not a black thing at that time  (1967-1968), in our unit our color was Marine Corps Green. <br><br>
We slept together, and ate together from the same can of C-rats and drank from the same canteens. We were also shot at and were shot at by the enemy regardless of our colors, the only rainbow coalition we understood was the color of the inter-mingled blood we spilled protecting one another. The enemy likewise didn't seem to care what color we were, as they shot at us with as equal determination.<br><br>
I wish I could tell you that it was like that always, but from what I have heard, Units after the mass demonstrations began and following the King so-called peaceful  rallies units began to experience problems in the states and it filtered into Nam. You may find problems there during the later years of the war. <br>
The NVA also got into the act and began to drop propaganda leaflets along trails in Nam urging Blacks to put down their arms and not fight for a government that was taking advantage of them. Still have some of those pamphlets. Some of those concepts were also used by anti-war demonstrators as evidence that more blacks were dying in Nam then whites but we now know that wasn<br>

